# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: xfs-filesystem
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:xfs-filesystem/allocate-on-flush] When blocks must be allocated to hold pending writes, disk space for the appended data is subtracted from the free-space counter, but not actually allocated in the free-space bitmap.
[src:xfs-filesystem/allocate-on-flush] Instead, the appended data are held in memory until they must be flushed to storage due to memory pressure, when the kernel decides to flush dirty buffers, or when the application performs the Unix *sync* system call, for example.
[src:xfs-filesystem/allocate-on-flush] This has the effect of batching together allocations into larger runs.
[src:xfs-filesystem/allocate-on-flush] Such delayed processing reduces CPU usage, and tends to reduce disk fragmentation, especially for files which grow slowly.
[src:xfs-filesystem/allocate-on-flush] It can also help in keeping allocations contiguous when there are several files growing at the same time.
[src:xfs-filesystem/allocate-on-flush] When used in conjunction with copy-on-write as it is in ZFS, it can convert slow random writes into fast sequential writes.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] A **journaling file system** is a file system that keeps track of changes not yet committed to the file system's main part by recording the goal of such changes in a data structure known as a "journal", which is usually a circular log.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] In the event of a system crash or power failure, such file systems can be brought back online more quickly with a lower likelihood of becoming corrupted.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Depending on the actual implementation, a journaling file system may only keep track of stored metadata, resulting in improved performance at the expense of increased possibility for data corruption.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Alternatively, a journaling file system may track both stored data and related metadata, while some implementations allow selectable behavior in this regard.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] In 1990 IBM introduced JFS in AIX 3.1 as one of the first UNIX commercial filesystems that implemented journaling.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] The next year the idea was popularized in a widely cited paper on log-structured file systems.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] This was subsequently implemented in Microsoft's Windows NT's NTFS filesystem in 1993, in Apple's HFS Plus filesystem in 1998, and in Linux's ext3 filesystem in 2001.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Updating file systems to reflect changes to files and directories usually requires many separate write operations.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] This makes it possible for an interruption (like a power failure or system crash) between writes to leave data structures in an invalid intermediate state.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Releasing the inode to the pool of free inodes.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Returning all disk blocks to the pool of free disk blocks.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] If a crash occurs after step 1 and before step 2, there will be an orphaned inode and hence a storage leak; if a crash occurs between steps 2 and 3, then the blocks previously used by the file cannot be used for new files, effectively decreasing the storage capacity of the file system.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Re-arranging the steps does not help, either.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] If step 3 preceded step 1, a crash between them could allow the file's blocks to be reused for a new file, meaning the partially deleted file would contain part of the contents of another file, and modifications to either file would show up in both.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] On the other hand, if step 2 preceded step 1, a crash between them would cause the file to be inaccessible, despite appearing to exist.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Detecting and recovering from such inconsistencies normally requires a complete walk of its data structures, for example by a tool such as fsck (the file system checker).
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] This must typically be done before the file system is next mounted for read-write access.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] If the file system is large and if there is relatively little I/O bandwidth, this can take a long time and result in longer downtimes if it blocks the rest of the system from coming back online.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] To prevent this, a journaled file system allocates a special area—the journal—in which it records the changes it will make ahead of time.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] After a crash, recovery simply involves reading the journal from the file system and replaying changes from this journal until the file system is consistent again.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] The changes are thus said to be atomic (not divisible) in that they either succeed (succeeded originally or are replayed completely during recovery), or are not replayed at all (are skipped because they had not yet been completely written to the journal before the crash occurred).
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Some file systems allow the journal to grow, shrink and be re-allocated just as a regular file, while others put the journal in a contiguous area or a hidden file that is guaranteed not to move or change size while the file system is mounted.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Some file systems may also allow *external journals* on a separate device, such as a solid-state drive or battery-backed non-volatile RAM.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Changes to the journal may themselves be journaled for additional redundancy, or the journal may be distributed across multiple physical volumes to protect against device failure.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] The internal format of the journal must guard against crashes while the journal itself is being written to.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Many journal implementations (such as the JBD2 layer in ext4) bracket every change logged with a checksum, on the understanding that a crash would leave a partially written change with a missing (or mismatched) checksum that can simply be ignored when replaying the journal at next remount.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] A *physical journal* logs an advance copy of every block that will later be written to the main file system.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] If there is a crash when the main file system is being written to, the write can simply be replayed to completion when the file system is next mounted.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] If there is a crash when the write is being logged to the journal, the partial write will have a missing or mismatched checksum and can be ignored at next mount.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Physical journals impose a significant performance penalty because every changed block must be committed *twice* to storage, but may be acceptable when absolute fault protection is required.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] A *logical journal* stores only changes to file metadata in the journal, and trades fault tolerance for substantially better write performance.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] A file system with a logical journal still recovers quickly after a crash, but may allow unjournaled file data and journaled metadata to fall out of sync with each other, causing data corruption.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] The free space map, to mark out an allocation of space for the to-be-appended data.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] The newly allocated space, to actually write the appended data.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] In a metadata-only journal, step 3 would not be logged.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] If step 3 was not done, but steps 1 and 2 are replayed during recovery, the file will be appended with garbage.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] The write cache in most operating systems sorts its writes (using the elevator algorithm or some similar scheme) to maximize throughput.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] To avoid an out-of-order write hazard with a metadata-only journal, writes for file data must be sorted so that they are committed to storage before their associated metadata.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] This can be tricky to implement because it requires coordination within the operating system kernel between the file system driver and write cache.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] An out-of-order write hazard can also occur if a device cannot write blocks immediately to its underlying storage, that is, it cannot flush its write-cache to disk due to deferred write being enabled.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] To complicate matters, many mass storage devices have their own write caches, in which they may aggressively reorder writes for better performance.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Some UFS implementations avoid journaling and instead implement soft updates: they order their writes in such a way that the on-disk file system is never inconsistent, or that the only inconsistency that can be created in the event of a crash is a storage leak.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] To recover from these leaks, the free space map is reconciled against a full walk of the file system at next mount.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] This garbage collection is usually done in the background.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] In log-structured file systems, the write-twice penalty does not apply because the journal itself *is* the file system: it occupies the entire storage device and is structured so that it can be traversed as would a normal file system.
[src:xfs-filesystem/journaling-file-system] This has the same correctness-preserving properties as a journal, without the write-twice overhead.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] XFS excels in the execution of parallel input/output (I/O) operations due to its design, which is based on allocation groups (a type of subdivision of the physical volumes in which XFS is used – also shortened to *AGs*).
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Because of this, XFS enables extreme scalability of I/O threads, file system bandwidth, and size of files and of the file system itself when spanning multiple physical storage devices.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] XFS ensures the consistency of data by employing metadata journaling and supporting write barriers.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Space allocation is performed via extents with data structures stored in B+ trees, improving the overall performance of the file system, especially when handling large files.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Delayed allocation assists in the prevention of file system fragmentation; online defragmentation is also supported.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Silicon Graphics began development of XFS ("X" was meant to be filled in later but never was) in 1993 for its UNIX System V based IRIX operating system.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] The file system was released under the GNU General Public License (GPL) in May 1999.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] A team led by Steve Lord at SGI ported XFS to Linux, and first support by a Linux distribution came in 2001.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] This support gradually became available in almost all Linux distributions.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Initial support for XFS in the Linux kernel came through patches from SGI.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] It merged into the Linux kernel mainline for the 2.6 series, and separately merged in February 2004 into the 2.4 series in version 2.4.25, making XFS almost universally available on Linux systems.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Gentoo Linux became the first Linux distribution to introduce an option for XFS as the default filesystem in mid-2002.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] FreeBSD added read-only support for XFS in December 2005, and in June 2006 introduced experimental write support.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] However, this was intended only as an aid in migration from Linux, not as a "main" file system.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] In 2009, version 5.4 of 64-bit Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL) Linux distribution contained the necessary kernel support for the creation and usage of XFS file systems, but lacked the corresponding command-line tools.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] The tools available from CentOS could operate for that purpose, and Red Hat also provided them to RHEL customers on request.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] RHEL 6.0, released in 2010, includes XFS support for a fee as part of Red Hat's "scalable file system add-on".
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Oracle Linux 6, released in 2011, also includes an option for using XFS.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] RHEL 7.0, released in June 2014, uses XFS as its default file system, including support for using XFS for the `/boot` partition, which previously was not practical due to bugs in the GRUB bootloader.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Linux kernel 4.8 in August 2016 added a new feature, "reverse mapping".
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] This work required changes to XFS's on-disk format.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Linux kernel 5.10, released in December 2020, included the new on-disk format XFS v5.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] This was a hard break, since the deprecated XFS v4 can not be converted to XFS v5.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Data on partitions formatted with XFS v4 has to be backed up to another partition or media in order to restore it after formatting the old partition with XFS v5, which completely wipes all data on it.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] The support for XFS v4 will be removed from the Linux kernel in September 2030.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] XFS v5 introduced "bigtime", to store inode timestamps as a 64-bit nanosecond counter instead of the traditional 32-bit seconds counter.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] This postpones the previous Year 2038 problem until the year 2486.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] The Gentoo Handbook, Gentoo Linux's official installation manual, has recommended XFS as the "all-purpose all-platform filesystem" since 28 Jun 2023, succeeding Ext4.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] XFS is a 64-bit file system and supports a maximum file system size of 8 exbibytes minus one byte (263 − 1 bytes), but limitations imposed by the host operating system can decrease this limit.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] 32-bit Linux systems limit the size of both the file and file system to 16 tebibytes.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] In modern computing, journaling is a capability which ensures consistency of data in the file system, despite any power outages or system crash that may occur.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] XFS provides journaling for file system metadata, where file system updates are first written to a serial journal before the actual disk blocks are updated.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] The journal is a circular buffer of disk blocks that is not read in normal file system operation.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] The XFS journal can be stored within the data section of the file system (as an internal log), or on a separate device to minimize disk contention.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] In XFS, the journal primarily contains entries that describe the portions of the disk blocks changed by filesystem operations.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Journal updates are performed asynchronously to avoid a decrease in performance speed.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] In the event of a system crash, file system operations which occurred immediately prior to the crash can be reapplied and completed as recorded in the journal, which is how data stored in XFS file systems remain consistent.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Recovery is performed automatically the first time the file system is mounted after the crash.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] The speed of recovery is independent of the size of the file system, instead depending on the amount of file system operations to be reapplied.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] XFS file systems are internally partitioned into *allocation groups*, which are equally sized linear regions within the file system.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Files and directories can span allocation groups.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Each allocation group manages its own inodes and free space separately, providing scalability and parallelism so multiple threads and processes can perform I/O operations on the same file system simultaneously.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] This architecture helps to optimize parallel I/O performance on systems with multiple processors and/or cores, as metadata updates can also be parallelized.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] The internal partitioning provided by allocation groups can be especially beneficial when the file system spans multiple physical devices, allowing optimal usage of throughput of the underlying storage components.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] If an XFS file system is to be created on a striped RAID array, a *stripe unit* can be specified when the file system is created.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] This maximizes throughput by ensuring that data allocations, inode allocations and the internal log (the journal) are aligned with the stripe unit.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Blocks used in files stored on XFS file systems are managed with variable length extents where one extent describes one or more contiguous blocks.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] This can shorten the list of blocks considerably, compared to file systems that list all blocks used by a file individually.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Block-oriented file systems manage space allocation with one or more block-oriented bitmaps; in XFS, these structures are replaced with an extent oriented structure consisting of a pair of B+ trees for each file system allocation group.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] One of the B+ trees is indexed by the length of the free extents, while the other is indexed by the starting block of the free extents.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] This dual indexing scheme allows for the highly efficient allocation of free extents for file system operations.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] The file system block size represents the minimum allocation unit.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] XFS allows file systems to be created with block sizes ranging between 512 bytes and 64 KB, allowing the file system to be tuned for the expected degree of usage.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] When many small files are expected, a small block size would typically maximize capacity, but for a system dealing mainly with large files, a larger block size can provide a performance efficiency advantage.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] XFS makes use of lazy evaluation techniques for file allocation.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] When a file is written to the buffer cache, rather than allocating extents for the data, XFS simply reserves the appropriate number of file system blocks for the data held in memory.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] The actual block allocation occurs only when the data is finally flushed to disk.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] This improves the chance that the file will be written in a contiguous group of blocks, reducing fragmentation problems and increasing performance.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] XFS provides a 64-bit sparse address space for each file, which allows both for very large file sizes, and for "holes" within files in which no disk space is allocated.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] As the file system uses an extent map for each file, the file allocation map size is kept small.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Where the size of the allocation map is too large for it to be stored within the inode, the map is moved into a B+ tree which allows for rapid access to data anywhere in the 64-bit address space provided for the file.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] XFS provides multiple data streams for files; this is made possible by its implementation of extended attributes.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] These allow the storage of a number of name/value pairs attached to a file.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Names are nul-terminated printable character strings which are up to 256 bytes in length, while their associated values can contain up to 64 KB of binary data.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] They are further subdivided into two namespaces: `root` and `user`.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Extended attributes stored in the root namespace can be modified only by the superuser, while attributes in the user namespace can be modified by any user with permission to write to the file.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Extended attributes can be attached to any kind of XFS inode, including symbolic links, device nodes, directories, etc.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] The `attr` utility can be used to manipulate extended attributes from the command line, and the `xfsdump` and `xfsrestore` utilities are aware of extended attributes, and will back up and restore their contents.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Many other backup systems do not support working with extended attributes.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] For applications requiring high throughput to disk, XFS provides a direct I/O implementation that allows non-cached I/O operations to be applied directly to the userspace.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Data is transferred between the buffer of the application and the disk using DMA, which allows access to the full I/O bandwidth of the underlying disk devices.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] XFS does not yet provide direct support for snapshots, as it currently expects the snapshot process to be implemented by the volume manager.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Taking a snapshot of an XFS filesystem involves temporarily halting I/O to the filesystem using the `xfs_freeze` utility, having the volume manager perform the actual snapshot, and then resuming I/O to continue with normal operations.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] The snapshot can then be mounted read-only for backup purposes.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Releases of XFS in IRIX incorporated an integrated volume manager called XLV.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] This volume manager has not been ported to Linux, and XFS works with standard LVM in Linux systems instead.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] In recent Linux kernels, the `xfs_freeze` functionality is implemented in the VFS layer, and is executed automatically when the Volume Manager's snapshot functionality is invoked.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] This was once a valuable advantage as the ext3 file system could not be suspended and the volume manager was unable to create a consistent "hot" snapshot to back up a heavily busy database.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Since Linux 2.6.29, the file systems ext3, ext4, GFS2 and JFS have the freeze feature as well.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] XFS provides the `xfs_growfs` utility to perform online expansion of XFS file systems.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] XFS filesystems can be grown so long as there is remaining unallocated space on the device holding the filesystem.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] This feature is typically used in conjunction with volume management, as otherwise the partition holding the filesystem will need enlarging separately.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] XFS supports a separate device called the realtime device, which uses a simple deterministic bitmap allocator instead of the more scalable but more complex B+ tree based allocator normally used in XFS.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] The realtime device was originally added to support Guaranteed-rate I/O, but acquired other uses later.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Today the most common usage is to place metadata on an SSDs while placing data on a hard drive.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] In Linux 4.9, XFS added support for sharing identifical blocks between files, which provides a fast way to clone files and to allower userspace tools to implement out of line Data deduplication.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] The reflink support is implemented using a new per-allocation group B+ tree tracking the number of references for each physical block, and changes to the write path to perform Copy-on-write when overwriting blocks with an elevated block count.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] As of Linux 6.10, XFS supports online file system checking and repair for all metadata.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] To support efficient rebuilds of the freespace tracking data structures, a reverse mapping (rmap) B+tree was added, and to provide redundant metadata for the file hierachy, parent pointers that are stored as extended attributes were added as well.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] As of Linux 7.0, XFS support autonomous self-healing based on these features, with the xfs_healer program automatically initiating repair action as needed.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Linux 6.15 added a new zoned allocator to support Zoned Storage, including hard drives using shingled-magnetic recording (SMR) and NVM Express SSDs using the zoned command set.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] The zoned allocator works on the realtime device and only stores file data.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Metadata uses the existing XFS allocator on the main device.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] To support SMR hard drives without conventional zones, zoned XFS adds support for an internal RT device, where the main and RT devices sit on the same Linux block device.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] The zoned allocator always writes out of place, and always writes sequentially in a limited number of open zones. and garbage collection is performed to evacuate valid blocks in partially used zones to create free zones used for further writes.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Zoned XFS can use multiple open zones and performs intelligent data placement, leading to better performance than other file systems on zoned storage, and even beating conventional file systems on regular SSDs for some use cases.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] XFS implemented the DMAPI interface to support Hierarchical Storage Management in IRIX.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] As of October 2010, the Linux implementation of XFS supported the required on-disk metadata for DMAPI implementation, but the kernel support was reportedly not usable.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] For some time, SGI hosted a kernel tree which included the DMAPI hooks, but this support has not been adequately maintained, although kernel developers have stated an intention to bring this support up to date.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] The XFS guaranteed-rate I/O system provides an API that allows applications to reserve bandwidth to the filesystem.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] XFS dynamically calculates the performance available from the underlying storage devices, and will reserve bandwidth sufficient to meet the requested performance for a specified time.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] This is a feature unique to the XFS file system.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Guaranteed rates can be "hard" or "soft", representing a trade off between reliability and performance; however, XFS will only allow "hard" guarantees if the underlying storage subsystem supports it.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] This facility is used mostly for real-time applications, such as video streaming.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Guaranteed-rate I/O was only supported under IRIX, and required special hardware for that purpose.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Attempting on a kernel beyond 3.17 to mount an IRIX XFS volume and write or run Fsck will result in filesystem corruption.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] IRIX remains on directory structure v2, whereas XFS introduced v3-v5 in later versions and dropped directory structure v2 around kernel 3.17.
[src:xfs-filesystem/xfs] Data loss and corruption will occur on later Linux kernels.
